00:07:23,240 --> 00:07:30,819
Okay, so before we get to the customer complaining language, I want to look at a phrase that the waiter used to apologize.

147
00:07:31,139 --> 00:07:33,220
He said, I do apologize.

148
00:07:33,220 --> 00:07:35,019
I do apologize.

149
00:07:35,220 --> 00:07:35,920
I do apologize.

150
00:07:36,360 --> 00:07:38,579
Now, why is this phrase so interesting?

151
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:44,620
Well, I mean, it's pretty easy to understand the meaning, but I want to look at why he added this verb do.

152
00:07:45,439 --> 00:07:54,560
Well, he added the verb do it to this phrase to make it seem a little bit stronger, to give a little more power to his apology.

153
00:07:55,139 --> 00:08:00,240
Right, so if you have an affirmative phrase like I apologize, it's good.

154
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:05,060
But if you want to give it a little bit more emphasis, you can say I do apologize.

155
00:08:05,519 --> 00:08:06,500
Why don't we give an example?

156
00:08:07,160 --> 00:08:11,139
So I might say this, Marco, I didn't know we had a party tonight.

157
00:08:11,759 --> 00:08:13,300
And I might say, what?

158
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:15,399
I did tell you about it last week.

159
00:08:15,879 --> 00:08:20,339
Right, so you're just giving a little bit more power to the statement that you told me.

160
00:08:21,040 --> 00:08:27,899
So this do, did, does becomes an auxiliary to make it more powerful, to give it more emphasis.

161
00:08:28,300 --> 00:08:28,819
Yeah, exactly.

162
00:08:28,819 --> 00:08:35,460
So a neat little phrase, something you can use if you want to make your apologies sound maybe a little bit stronger.

163
00:08:36,220 --> 00:08:38,799
Alright, now moving on to the next phrase.

164
00:08:39,200 --> 00:08:41,659
He was complaining about the food and it was terrible.

165
00:08:41,820 --> 00:08:45,500
And he said, I'm shelling out my hard-earned bucks.

166
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,940
